# PLACEHOLDER — replace this file with the armored Zibby APT public key.
#
# scripts/publish-apt.mjs will refuse to upload this file as long as it
# doesn't start with `-----BEGIN PGP PUBLIC KEY BLOCK-----`, so it is safe
# to ship in the repo.
#
# One-time operator setup (matches the runbook at the top of
# scripts/publish-apt.mjs):
#
#   1. Generate the dedicated APT signing key on a trusted workstation:
#        gpg --quick-generate-key "Zibby APT Signing <noreply@zibby.dev>" rsa4096 default 5y
#
#   2. Stash the armored private key in AWS Secrets Manager:
#        gpg --armor --export-secret-keys "Zibby APT Signing" > /tmp/zibby-apt-private.asc
#        AWS_PROFILE=zibby aws secretsmanager create-secret \
#          --name /zibby/prod/apt-signing-key \
#          --description "Armored private key used to sign dl.zibby.app/apt Release metadata" \
#          --secret-string file:///tmp/zibby-apt-private.asc
#        shred -u /tmp/zibby-apt-private.asc
#
#   3. Export the armored public key and OVERWRITE this file:
#        gpg --armor --export "Zibby APT Signing" > dist/apt/key.gpg
#
#   4. Commit dist/apt/key.gpg to the agent-ops repo. (Public key only —
#      the private key never leaves Secrets Manager.)
#
#   5. From now on, every `node scripts/publish-apt.mjs` run pulls the
#      private key from Secrets Manager into a per-run GNUPGHOME, signs
#      Release → InRelease + Release.gpg, re-uploads this public key as
#      `s3://<bucket>/apt/key.gpg`, then wipes the GNUPGHOME.
#
# NOTE: goreleaser will wipe everything else under dist/ when run with
# --clean. This file survives because it lives in dist/apt/, which is
# gitignored-from-but-not-deleted-by goreleaser. If a goreleaser run blows
# this file away, restore it from git: `git checkout dist/apt/key.gpg`.
